A recursive DNS lookup occurs when a DNS server forwards requests it cannot answer to additional DNS servers until it finds a valid answer. This original DNS server then relays the response to the DNS client that originated the DNS request. Most common DNS deployments utilize recursive DNS lookups in the form of DNS forwarders.

	&nbsp;

	A DNS request is the initial request a DNS client sends to a DNS server.

	&nbsp;

	In the case of a recursive DNS lookup, the DNS server also sends a DNS request to other DNS servers.

	In a DNS reply, a DNS server replies to a DNS request with a name-to-address resolution.

	&nbsp;

	A DNS cache is the mechanism that enables a DNS client and DNS server to store recent DNS requests to alleviate the need to have to complete the full DNS request and DNS reply process several times for the same name-to-address resolution.

