	The question asks about configuring a router interface, to support 802.1Q trunking, on a subinterface. To achieve those goals, the subinterface must be created, along with the encapsulation dot1q vlan-id subcommand.

	Of the four answers, two incorrect answers do not include the the&nbsp;encapsulation dot1q&nbsp;vlan-id&nbsp;subcommand. Of the two answers that include the subcommand, one shows the first command creating a subinterface (interface fastethernet 0/1.2), which is the correct answer. The other incorrect answer shows the configuration of a physical interface (interface fastethernet 0/1); the&nbsp;encapsulation dot1q&nbsp;vlan-id&nbsp;will not work as a subcommand under a physical interface.&nbsp;

To enable router-on-a-stick on a router subinterface, you must (1) configure the subinterface with an IP address using the ip address address mask subcommand, and (2) configure 802.1Q encapsulation for that VLAN using the&nbsp;encapsulation dot1q vlan-id&nbsp;subcommand.

	For the incorrect answers, you can configure the speed and duplex on the port itself, but using interface subcommands, but not subinterface subcommands (the question asks for commands on a subinterface). Another incorrect answer mentions the configuration of an IP route. You do not need to configure any routes; instead, the router will automatically create a connected route for the subnet off each subinterface once the subinterface is up/up and has an IP address configured.

	&nbsp;

The switch&nbsp;show interfaces trunk command&nbsp;verifies&nbsp;which interfaces trunk. It lists all interfaces currently operating as a trunk.&nbsp;

The show vlans command lists trunking information on IOS-based routers when configured to use ROAS. So, while useful, it would be useful only on the router and not the switch.

The other two answers list non-existent commands in switches.

Each SVI gives a switch a layer-3 interface that connects internally to some VLAN. Configuring multiple SVIs on a single Layer 3 switch gives that switch multiple layer-3 interfaces connected to the various VLANs, so that the switch can route IP traffic between the subnets that reside in those VLANs.

	For the incorrect answers, note that the SVI interfaces do nothing in support of layer 2 forwarding functions. An SVI is often used to configure an IP address on a switch to allow remote management, but the question asks why a switch would need multiple SVIs, and to support remote management, a single SVI is needed.&nbsp;

